The paper discusses the relationship between language and cognition, specifically the existence of a name strategy in memory and its implications for philosophy of language and mathematics. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including computational linguistics (cs.CL), machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computational complexity (cs.CC), and cryptography and security (cs.CR) which may be relevant to the discussion of know-how representations and minimum duplication of resources.
